ierc_1a: My anger stemmed from a domino effect of events. During the summer heading into my first quarter of college, my parents forced me to go on a trip to Las Vegas with them and, even though I was grateful for a trip not everyone gets to experience, I wasn't happy throughout the trip, because I had nothing to do. When I got back, my aunt invited me to go to the beach, but the Vegas trip tired me out and I wanted to do something I actually wanted to do. Unfortunately, my parents and aunt ridiculed me for not going, saying I was lazy. Then at night, when I wanted to eat at home, considering we at out everyday as Vegas, my parents again forced me to go with them. When we got back home, I was finally able to do something I enjoyed, video games. However, before I could even play for 30 minutes, my mom started yelling at me to go to bed and threatened to throw away my xbox, something I payed for myself. At that point I was extremely angry of having absolutely no control over my life. I was frustrated at never having a say in anything and never getting options. I was angry at constantly pushing aside my happiness and being ridiculed for just taking time to enjoy the things I liked.
ierc_1b: I was angry and sad at the same time. I was made of all the things that happened, but also sad that my parents didn't consider how I was feeling at the time. I didn't want to interact with anyone the next few days and locked myself in my room. I was tired of living a life my parents wanted, not the one I wanted.
ierc_2: My dad finally sat me and my mom down and we all had a discussion about why I was so angry. I told them about why those events made me feel like my life was being controlled, even though I was 18 years old already. My dad said he understood how all the events that happened could've made me feel restricted from simply living my own life. My mom didn't see it that way, but thats the difference between them. My dad sees and treats me like a man or an adult, while my mom still sees me as her little boy and thus treats me like one. My mom told me I was acting out and being disobedient. However, my whole childhood, I've foregone birthday parties with friends, events, basketball games, vacations to do things my parents wanted. I never enjoyed school, but I went to the library to study for my parents. My dad understood this, but also told me that isolating myself wouldn't fix any problems. So he made a deal with me. I would get to dictate my own life more, now that I was older. This meant a giving me a choice on whether I wanted to participate. This also meant not isolating myself any longer and communicating my anger sooner in the future and not letting it build up. My mom on the other hand, was now angry at me and my dad. She went on her phone and told my aunts how rude I was to want some independence in my life as an adult. I still live under her roof so I still abide by her rules, but having to live a life thats only in the realm of want my parents condemned seemed unfair to me.

ierc_2: Typically, on the way home from a tournament, about 10 minutes into the drive, my dad would begin speaking to me, asking me questions such as, "How do you feel", "What do you think happened during that match" and so on. At this point I'm calm but still deeply angry or frustrated as any normal person would be. My dad doesn't necessarily try to make me feel better after a match, he doesn't say things like "You played really good", or "You did your best". But this is because he knows that him saying such things won't make me feel better one bit, because I don't like getting praise after I lose, especially if I know I played bad. Instead, my dad searches for the reasons I lost, relays them to me, and tells me some things I can do better or things I need to work on.

We chose the latter. It wasn't until the last 2 weeks in November that it really started to hit us that he was actively dying and he passed the Sunday before Thanksgiving.
ierc_1b: I was sad and scared. I couldn't control my crying. While I wasn't the closest to my grandfather, I still loved him and he was my mother's biological father. I wanted to be the one comforting, not crying.
ierc_2: This was the first time I kind of received some emotional support from my parent, and it was the first time I went to her for any emotional support. She told me that there's nothing we can do about it, so we shouldn't be too upset. For the first time, I wanted a hug from her and my family. Normally, I dislike hugs, but the hug helped a lot this time around.

ierc_1a: I have a legitimate prescription for marijuana from an actual licensed physician (not one of those for profit websites online) that I used to treat some insomnia and lack of hunger. Being from a Korean household, I knew that any sort of "drug" even widely accepted ones like weed were absolutely taboo so I never brought it up with them because I feared their reaction. One day, they found a couple of my things and before I ever had a chance to tell them anything or explain myself, they went ballistic. Even after voicing my side of the issue, they seemed unwilling to bend so I was extremely frustrated while living at their house. Here I was, with legitimate reasons for using marijuana, and my parents were making me feel like a criminal for it. Telling me about how it was a gateway drug, how it would spiral me into homelessness, etc.
ierc_1b: Sad, angry, confused. Basically a whole jumble of negative emotions.
ierc_2: A couple weeks afterwards, I asked my parents if we could revisit the conversation that we had because I felt that it wasn't fair to me at all and it was proving to have a negative impact on my life. My insomnia returned and I started to eat less and less every day. Whether they had time to think since our last conversation or they noticed that I was looking a little worse for wear, they were much more understanding now. Asking me questions about how strong my dosage was, if I've ever felt that I was maybe addicted, if it's genuinely been a useful tool in my life. Though it wasn't much, these questions showed me that they were open to having a conversation with me about something that they had no interest in.

ierc_1a: It was our yearly family vacation, this year we went to Hawaii. The first four days of the trip were great. Beautiful beaches, wonderful people, amazing food, it was like we were in heaven. The first four days were perfect. Come the fourth day is when things take a turn for the worst. I just got out of the pool at this time when I get a phone call from one of my friends. He asked me if my boyfriend worked at Taco Bell and this made me very suspicious. I called him to ask and he said that one of his friends told him how my boyfriend was going on a date with another girl when I wasn't there. Outraged, I called my boyfriend at the time to ask what happen and he got mad at me because I didn't believe him that she was just a friend. He ended up breaking things off with me when I was supposed to be having the dream vacation of the life time.
ierc_1b: I was all the bad emotions you can think of. I was shocked, anxious, nervous, enraged, and most of all really sad.
ierc_2: When I went back to our hotel room I was clearly distraught. Screaming, yelling, crying, all the bad things you can think of. My mom ended up getting mad at me for being upset and said I had ruined the family vacation. She got mad at me at the time I needed her the most and that's what hurt the most. My dad left for a bit and when he returned he got me ice cream and he gave me a foot massage. He never had to deal with anything like this before because I am his first born daughter but he had heard before ice cream helps with things like this so he got me ice cream and proceeded to give me a foot rub. It wasn't just that that made me feel better but it was the fact that out of my entire family he sympothized with what I was going through and what I was feeling and didn't blame me for being upset.
